docs.abstract: The Times’s community team rounded up a selection of reader reactions to a recent story about the workplace culture at Amazon.
docs.snippet: The Times’s community team rounded up a selection of reader reactions to a recent story about the workplace culture at Amazon.
docs.lead_paragraph: Toilet paper-delivering drones may not be a thing (yet), but history was made over the weekend when Jodi Kantor and David Streitfeld’s exposé on workplace practices at Amazon became the most commented-on story at The New York Times.

headline.main: A Deluge of Comments From Readers With an Opinion About Amazon

docs.abstract: The company’s chief told employees that he didn’t recognize the “soulless, dystopian workplace” that he said was depicted in a New York Times article.
docs.snippet: The company’s chief told employees that he didn’t recognize the “soulless, dystopian workplace” that he said was depicted in a New York Times article.
docs.lead_paragraph: For 20 years, Amazon has reveled in its toughness. “Work hard” are the first two words of a company motto. An oft-repeated line from Jeff Bezos, the founder and chief executive, calls the company culture “friendly and intense, but if push comes to shove we’ll settle for intense.”

headline.main: Jeff Bezos and Amazon Employees Join Debate Over Its Culture
headline.print_headline: Bezos Says Amazon Has No Room for ‘Callous’ Acts

byline.original: By David Streitfeld and Jodi Kantor
